I guess this should be
```suggestion
lemma leftKanExtensionUnit_leftKanExtension_map_leftKanExtensionObjIsoColimit_hom (X : D)
```

```suggestion
    colimit.ι (proj L X ⋙ F) f :=
```
also appears elsewhere.

I'm surprised this is useful. Are you sure that the lemmas below are not sufficient? My expectation would be that the coherence proof in `Final.lean` becomes simpler if you only use the lemmas below and do not "unfold" `colimitIsoColimitGrothendieck` in this way, because then you essentially have to reprove one of the lemmas below, but with a lot more stuff around that can make the automation go haywire.
As discussed, please check how much work it would be to generalize the universes here using `AsSmall` and either implement it or leave a comment here somewhere that the universes can be generalized.

I'm surprised that we don't seem to have
```lean
import Mathlib

universe v₁ v₂ v₃ u₁ u₂ u₃

open Opposite

namespace CategoryTheory

variable {A : Type u₁} [Category.{v₁} A]
variable {B : Type u₂} [Category.{v₂} B]
variable {T : Type v₃} [Category.{v₃} T]
variable (L : A ⥤ T) (R : B ⥤ T)

@[simps]
def Comma.opFunctor : Comma L R ⥤ (Comma R.op L.op)ᵒᵖ where
  obj X := ⟨op X.right, op X.left, op X.hom⟩ 
  map f := ⟨op f.right, op f.left, Quiver.Hom.unop_inj (by simp)⟩

@[simps!]
def Comma.opFunctorCompFst :
    Comma.opFunctor L R ⋙ (Comma.fst _ _).op ≅
      Comma.snd _ _ ⋙ (opOpEquivalence _).inverse :=
  Iso.refl _

@[simps!]
def Comma.opFunctorCompSnd :
    Comma.opFunctor L R ⋙ (Comma.snd _ _).op ≅
      Comma.fst _ _ ⋙ (opOpEquivalence _).inverse :=
  Iso.refl _

@[simps]
def Comma.unopFunctor : Comma L.op R.op ⥤ (Comma R L)ᵒᵖ where
  obj X := ⟨X.right.unop, X.left.unop, X.hom.unop⟩ 
  map f := ⟨f.right.unop, f.left.unop, Quiver.Hom.op_inj (by simpa using f.w.symm)⟩

@[simps!]
def Comma.unopFunctorCompFst : Comma.unopFunctor L R ⋙ (Comma.fst _ _).op ≅ Comma.snd _ _ :=
  Iso.refl _

@[simps!]
def Comma.unopFunctorCompSnd : Comma.unopFunctor L R ⋙ (Comma.snd _ _).op ≅ Comma.fst _ _ :=
  Iso.refl _

@[simps]
def Comma.opEquiv : Comma L R ≌ (Comma R.op L.op)ᵒᵖ where
  functor := Comma.opFunctor L R
  inverse := (Comma.unopFunctor R L).leftOp
  unitIso := NatIso.ofComponents (fun X => Iso.refl _)
  counitIso := NatIso.ofComponents (fun X => Iso.refl _)

end CategoryTheory
```
but with this it should hopefully be possible to deduce the dual statement about initial functors?
